result.execSummary: Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Cory John Nycz in court with attorney Christian Thomas Eichenlaub.  Megan Patricia Carmody appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Parties prepared to proceed to Court trial.  Hearing proceeded.  Jury Waiver received and filed.  Court held colloquy with the defendant as to jury waiver.  

PHASE I:

Parties in receipt of report dated July 22, 2015 authored by Dr. John Pankiewicz.  Parties stipulate to the facts and request that the court examine the criminal complaint.  The state calls no witnesses; state rests subject to rebuttal.  Defendant examined by the Court as to his right to testify/right to remain silent.  The Court accepts waiver and finds that the defendant freely, voluntarily, and intelligently consented to the factual basis for these charges and to waiving his right to testify.  Defense calls no witnesses.  Defense rests.  Court sets forth findings and rulings.  The Court finds the defendant culpable of Counts 1 and 2.

PHASE II:

The Court finds that the defendant again waives his right to jury trial.  Parties stipulate that Dr. Pankiewicz is an expert in the area of forensic psychology.  The state is not challenging 7-22-15 report; parties stipulate to findings in said report.  Parties advise the Court that they disagree as to placement.  The Court sets forth findings; defendant found not guilty and not guilty by reason of mental disease or defect.  Argument heard as to length of commitment; parties disagree.  In chambers discussion held with both counsel.  The Court to needs additional time to consider argument of counsel to determine appropriate length of commitment per statute. The Court to issue written decision.  The Court DOES NOT commit the defendant at this time.  Defense waives time limit as to determination of placement.  The Court orders outstanding bench warrant cancelled.  The Court orders signature bond reinstated at this time.  The Court orders the defendant to comply with the following conditions of bail: possess no dangerous weapons or firearms, follow doctors orders, and comply with veterans programming.  State requests status date prior to hearing/decision date.  Appearance of the defendant waived for 9-18-15 status date.
  Status conference scheduled for September 18, 2015 at 08:30 am.  Hearing scheduled for October 30, 2015 at 10:00 am.
